RELATED OPERATING UNITS




Arias I
                                                        




H.N.E. has held the concession to the hydroelectric operation of Arias 1 since 1973, for a maximum volume of flow of 40 m3/s. The plant still houses a 700 KVA Alternator and turbine, manufactured in 1905. It is out of service but is being kept for reasons of historical interest... read more







Arias II
                                                        




Arias 2 plant administrative concession was first granted in 1915. For many years the maximum flow was of 10 m3/s, but since 1979 that maximum flow volume is 40 m3/s. The plant still houses a 700 KVA Alternator and turbine, manufactured in 1905. It is out of service but is being kept for reasons of historical interest... read more







Ariéstolas
                                                        




H.N.E. has held the concession to the hydroelectric operation of Ariéstolas since 1955, when it was transferred from Eléctrica del Cinca, for a maximum volume of flow of 20 m3/s... read more







Barasona
                                                        




Barasona (Joaquín Costa) Reservoir on the River Ésera, was built by the Hydrographical Confederation of the River Ebro, between 1927-1931, to run into the Aragón and Cataluña canal. The concession to the hydroelectric operation of this reservoir have been held by H.N.E. since 1942, getting the power plant to work in 1949... read more







Carantoña
                                                        




Carantoña plant is a station with an open flow diversion channel passing through a dam, canal, load chamber, penstock, the plant and the pipes returning to the river. As this is a run-of-the-river station, it depends exclusively on the water regime of the river itself... read more







Castrelo
                                                        




Castrelo plant consists of a run-of-the-river plant built in 1956 with a diversion dam built in brickwork, from where the water is taken. A diversion channel, with various branches set in the hillside and in tunnels, leads the water to the load chamber. read more







El Ciego
                                                        




H.N.E. was awarded the concession for the hydroelectric operation of the El Ciego Plant in 1952, as an extension to the hydroelectric operation of Barasona, for a maximum flow volume of 12 m3/s... read more







Fervenza
                                                        




Fervenza is an hydroelectric plant built in 1966 at the base of a dam with regulating reservoir... read more







Nuevo Pindo
                                                        




Nuevo Pindo plant was built in 2004 as part of an extension of the concession of the operation of the Santa Eugenia power station. It is supplied through a diversion from the penstock of Santa Eugenia II. It is situated in a one-storey building, with a tiled roof supported by wooden panels, pillars and with stone and brick walls... read more







Puente Olveira
                                                        




The plant consist on a composed open flow diversion channel, with the water flowing through a dam, an intake construction, a diversion tunnel, load chamber, penstock plant and the pipes discharging to the river. The dam was built in 1966 and it is 26 m high and the crest is 107 m long... read more







St. Béron
                                                        




The Saint-Béron power plant was built on the Guiers river in 1892. This hydroelectric plant supplied for almost a century a ferro-alloys plant which was closed in 1985. The power plant is under the concession regime since 1995 until 2035. The power plant yearly production is around 55 GWh, which is sold to the grid... read more







Santa Eugenia I-II
                                                        




The Santa Eugenia dam was in 1988, with a height of 87 m and a crest length of 280m. Santa Eugenia I and Santa Eugenia II plants both benefit from this dam to produce energy... read more







Villelongue
                                                        




The Villelongue power plant was built in 1895. FerroPEM Pierrefitte plant has been running it ever since and has held the last concession to the hydroelectric operation since 2000, for the next 40 years. The current rights will then expire in 2040. The maximum flow is approximately 1.5m3/s during spring months. The power plant yearly production is around 30 GWh, which is almost entirely... read more












